node.text: It’s #NationalMothWeek, and I always feel like a proud parent with the need to share this beautiful Cecropia Moth. I found her cocoon in early April 2019; she emerged at the end of May, and in my opinion, was one of the most stunning cecropias I’ve ever seen. These moths are the largest native moth we have in North America. I’ll spend the week talking about moths and sharing other folks' educational work to showcase how essential moths are to our ecosystems.

node.text: I missed world snake day; I’ll be honest, I fell asleep while editing this photo, but I wanted to post this Eyelash Viper. In Costa Rica, Eyelash vipers come in many colors, but when they’re pure yellow like this, I find the most stunning. Snakes are unfortunately misunderstood and don’t get the appreciation they deserve. A good rule of thumb, if you leave a snake alone, it will leave you alone. A snake will not chase you or bite for any reason than fear for their life.

node.text: Here’s that second photo of the Indigo Bunting that didn’t post on my previous post. This individual had been born the year before and didn’t have the full brilliant blue plumage yet. For folks that don’t know, the blue coloration in these feathers does not come from what these birds eat. It comes from the structure of the feathers and how the light reflects. The simple way to think of it is the red and yellow wavelengths get canceled out, and the blues are amplified.

node.text: This hummingbird used to be named Blue-throated Goldentail, which was fitting, but the new name of Blue-throated Sapphire seems even more appropriate and I think this photo displays that. They’re a species that can typically be found in dry habitats in the tropics, I encountered them often in northwestern Costa Rica.

node.text: When I was offering prints for the @cocobolonature fundraiser, someone brought up this Ringed Kingfisher, and I couldn’t help but post a version. It also was very fitting since the first time I experienced this large bird in the hand was at Cocobolo. You might be familiar with the Belted Kingfisher common across the US, but this is the larger southern counterpart. Unlike the Belted, this species likes to sit along waterways for hours waiting to prey on a fish. If that hunting method doesn’t give you dinosaur vibes, the rest of the looks sure should (don’t @ me @marchoftheplankton). They also have quite the call, also very raptor-like; I love hearing them along the waterways of the tropics.

node.text:
@cocobolonature is the first place I ever went to in the tropics back in 2006. It was the spot that made me fall in love with the rainforest and the unique flora and fauna. Right now, it needs help, and usually, the research station is buzzing with students, researchers, and classes on a wide variety of topics. Unfortunately, it’s been closed for the past year, unable to generate the necessary income to pay for guards and maintain the facilities. A @gofundme has been started to help cover the costs until the station resumes operations. There’s a lot of rainforest to help protect and many critical species that call the area home, so having people patrolling to stop things like poaching of large cats is a concern. If you can donate any amount, you can choose any photo from my feed and receive a digital print. Just send me a message with proof of your donation, the image you’d like, and your email. I appreciate any support folks can give, even sharing about it helps get the word out. 

Pictured is a female Royal Flycatcher from Cocobolo, and I’ve yet to see a place with more Royal Flycatchers, reason enough to want to help protect this rainforest.

We’ve only got a month left of our @shade.raised.organic X @wildbirdresearch coffee collaboration. 

Looking for a way to help birds just by sipping your morning coffee? Well, you’re in luck. We’ve partnered with Shade Raised Organic Coffees, SROTM  , for a new coffee line that helps fundraise for our spring and summer field research to help us reveal the habitat needs and population trends of migratory birds.

Who’s ready to order more delicious, sustainable coffee that supports our work to your morning routine? Tap the link in my story or bio. 

Species pictured: Ruby-throated Hummingbird.

node.text: This week at @wildbirdresearch New Jersey station, we had quite the day, over 100 birds, tons of this year's babies, and a bushel of Orchard Orioles, well technically a “pitch.” This was one of the three adult males we had, and we also had two second-year males, a female and a local fledgling. The Orchard Oriole seems to play second fiddle to the Baltimore Orioles, but that rich autumn orange they sport is stunning.

node.text: While the brilliant ruby red gorget feathers tell you this is an adult male Ruby-throated Hummingbird, the bill of Hummingbirds will also tell you about their age. In the next slide, we have this adult male bill, and it’s smooth without many corrugations (grooves). The following photo is of a young male with a lot of corrugation marks, and these are growth marks as the birds' bill was growing. Think of it like growth rings on a tree, but as they mature, they fade away; it can be instrumental in aging other species of hummingbirds that don’t have as defined plumages.

node.text: This Kentucky Warbler family being well taken care of by the father. While males and females bring food into the nest, the male will rarely bring food for the chicks and female, but I watched this male get something for everyone.

node.text: What’s the Fiery-throated without the Talamanca Hummingbird, these highland hummingbirds are usually found together fighting over resources. I have a hard time deciding which of the two I prefer, and they’re both such stunning species.
